{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d1aef622-2105-42cb-b913-5c656fa213df","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the system automatically generates a **crash report**. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**\n   `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **System-level reports:**\n   `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_<date>_<machine>.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions). They contain the stack trace, exception type, and thread state.\n\nYou can also open **Console.app** → sidebar → **Crash Reports** to browse them.\n\n**For a core dump** (full memory dump), macOS disables them by default. To enable:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n/usr/libexec/PlistBuddy -c \"Add :com.apple.security.get-task-allow bool true\" entitlements.plist\ncodesign -s - --entitlements entitlements.plist --force ./YourApp\n```\n\nCore dumps land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7cbd3839-ac50-4eb9-b46d-e2eaf4245123","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":306},"id":"2412bfeb-773a-471e-bd55-edb905bda165","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:00:48.487Z","parentId":"6093fe07-7280-48e3-8301-285066a8618c"}
